column3: When I was a kid, my parents used to read me a story from a children's book. I love the art of storytelling and now I do the same. But, instead of telling a story from a children's book, I do storytelling with data (not for kids, obviously). As a data analyst, I gather insight by crunching a bunch of words and numbers, share the data through visualization, and communicate my analysis results and recommendations to the stakeholders using the art of storytelling. In my opinion, extracting and processing the data using various tools is an important skill that every data analyst should master, but data analysis is more than that. A good data analyst should have really good business acumen and deductive reasoning skills to make useful and effective recommendations out of data and communicate them to the stakeholders. So, for me, the thing that makes a data analyst stand out from the others is remarkable communication, storytelling, and prescriptive analytic skills. After all, data analyst is a data-driven decision-maker, right? Albert Einstein once said: "Once you stop learning, you start dyingâ€. Data analytics is a never-ending learning process, there will be a better and better method and solution. As a data analyst, I am proficient in using programming languages such as Python and MySQL to extract and delve into the data to identify the problems that need to be solved and business metrics related to it, doing structured analysis using both exploratory and statistical methods, presenting it using data visualization software like Tableau or Excel, and communicate my analysis and recommendation to the stakeholders through a presentation. Does it stop right there? No. I will always be in the continuous learning process to develop myself and sharpen my skills. I can't promise you that I will be the best data analyst in the world. But, I can promise you that I will be a better data analyst every time.

column3: I'm a person who really love to teach other, sharing knowledge and experience, mentoring, and other stuff with aim to make others understand. Since I was in high school, teaching my friends in study group (math and science subjects) has been my interest. Throughout my college years, I had been a lab and teaching assistant in total 13 subjects. I also have been working in 5 formal and informal tutoring centers as tutor in math and physics subjects. Well, those are my experience about teaching. But I'm not stopping yet. Along with my partner, I created education-based YouTube channel, TPB Santuy, with purpose to help undergraduate students to understand Elementary Physics and Basic Calculus. Working on this YouTube project channel really brings another challenge to myself. From this project, I've learned about very basic video editing, efficient and effective presentation, and some simulation tools. Aside from that, I've also become interested in computer programming language. I took several classes about computation throughout college years. Many of the projects from the class are really interesting such as simulating motion of a particle under certain circumstance, analyzing frequency spectra from musical notes, and simulating bottleneck traffic in highway road. Most of the projects were done using MATLAB computing tools. I also did my thesis project (which talks about light scattering from nano sized particles) using MATLAB. Nevertheless, computing never cease in just one programming language/tools. I began to learn another programming language such as Python and R as I became interested in data analytics and machine learning topics. My first project in Python was very challenging. I had to implement Monte Carlo â€“ Markov Chain method to obtain some parameters from an astronomical model. I managed to handle that project after 1-2 months experimenting. The next following projects I took were about machine learning and data mining techniques such as decision tree, regression, basic neural network etc. During the quarantine time, I have decided to intensively learn data analytics and machine learning using Python, R, and SQL. Iâ€™ve learned about data cleaning, data visualization, supervised and unsupervised learning, hyperparameters tuning, and pipeline. Currently, Iâ€™m working on several projects from Kaggle datasets and competition. All these projects are really helpful and interesting for my learning experience. I hope I can share my project reports as soon as possible. ,Data Analyst at Tokopedia,Jakarta Raya, Indonesia
